00:53:47.827 --> 00:53:49.639
(laughing)

00:53:49.639 --> 00:53:51.523
My dissertation was a comparison of

00:53:51.523 --> 00:53:54.128
New York and California
conversational styles.

00:53:54.128 --> 00:53:55.208
- [Woman In Blue Shirt] That's
what I wanted to ask you.

00:53:55.208 --> 00:53:56.208
Do you have a book?

00:53:56.208 --> 00:53:57.208
You have a book on mothers
and daughters, and women.

00:53:57.208 --> 00:54:00.992
Do you have a book on East
Coast versus West Coast?

00:54:00.992 --> 00:54:02.563
That direct stuff you
would just talking about

00:54:02.563 --> 00:54:05.027
at the end of your
speech is my life story.

00:54:05.027 --> 00:54:07.045
And I've gotten in trouble so many times.

00:54:07.045 --> 00:54:09.501
30 years out here and I can't fix it.

00:54:09.501 --> 00:54:10.510
Do you have a book on that?

00:54:10.510 --> 00:54:11.909
- I do.
- Or can you point me

00:54:11.909 --> 00:54:13.295
to a book on that?

00:54:13.295 --> 00:54:15.455
And also, the last piece of that is,

00:54:15.455 --> 00:54:16.796
what advice do you have for someone who

00:54:16.796 --> 00:54:18.734
obviously can't change
the way she communicates,

00:54:18.734 --> 00:54:21.686
and yet gets in trouble
for that very thing?

00:54:21.686 --> 00:54:23.061
- Yeah, okay.

00:54:23.061 --> 00:54:24.881
So just let me say a little bit about,

00:54:24.881 --> 00:54:26.373
so it was my dissertation.

00:54:26.373 --> 00:54:27.855
It's a book.

00:54:27.855 --> 00:54:29.441
It's an academic book, but it's pretty,

00:54:29.441 --> 00:54:31.987
everything I write it pretty readable.

00:54:31.987 --> 00:54:34.178
The book is called Conversational Style:

00:54:34.178 --> 00:54:36.886
Analyzing Talk Among Friends.

00:54:36.886 --> 00:54:38.205
And then I have the book called,

00:54:38.205 --> 00:54:39.772
That's Not What I Meant, which is just all

00:54:39.772 --> 00:54:41.717
the things that can differ,
including the things

00:54:41.717 --> 00:54:43.787
that differ New York and California.

00:54:43.787 --> 00:54:48.174
But this may be some of
what you're experiencing.

00:54:48.174 --> 00:54:50.270
It was so shocking to me,

00:54:50.270 --> 00:54:51.858
and I have more to say
about this tomorrow,

00:54:51.858 --> 00:54:53.922
that I'd be accused of being rude

00:54:53.922 --> 00:54:58.013
when in New York I was
considered overly polite.

00:54:58.013 --> 00:54:59.686
- Thank you.
Yes.

00:54:59.686 --> 00:55:01.204
- I had friends who literally would say

00:55:01.204 --> 00:55:03.136
I'm not really New York Jewish,

00:55:03.136 --> 00:55:04.168
which is what I am.

00:55:04.168 --> 00:55:06.226
It's just in New York
it's easier being Jewish.

00:55:06.226 --> 00:55:09.622
I must really be a wasp,
because I'm so indirect,

00:55:09.622 --> 00:55:11.572
and so you know.

00:55:11.572 --> 00:55:14.161
And suddenly here, I
was being called rude.

00:55:14.161 --> 00:55:18.540
And it's things like talking
along to show enthusiasm,

00:55:18.540 --> 00:55:22.285
and you're perceived as
indirect, as interrupting.

00:55:22.285 --> 00:55:25.118
The length of pause between turns.

00:55:27.350 --> 00:55:29.232
And this can vary, not just
New York and California,

00:55:29.232 --> 00:55:31.859
but Californians and New England.

00:55:31.859 --> 00:55:33.389
Or New England and the South.

00:55:33.389 --> 00:55:35.331
Anytime two people are talking,

00:55:35.331 --> 00:55:39.784
if one is conducting a
slightly shorter pause,

00:55:39.784 --> 00:55:41.670
you get the feeling that the other person

00:55:41.670 --> 00:55:44.223
has nothing to say, and
you wanna be a nice person

00:55:44.223 --> 00:55:46.856
and save the conversation,
so you start speaking.

00:55:46.856 --> 00:55:50.328
And if that person is waiting
for a slightly longer pause,

00:55:50.328 --> 00:55:53.509
it never comes, and they feel interrupted.

00:55:53.509 --> 00:55:56.143
So, yeah, and on, and on,
and on, things like that.

00:55:56.143 --> 00:55:57.164
What can you do?

00:55:57.164 --> 00:55:58.740
I'd say meta-communicate.

00:55:58.740 --> 00:56:00.074
Talk about it.

00:56:00.074 --> 00:56:04.286
That example I gave was my
really close friend, Tamara.

00:56:04.286 --> 00:56:08.036
Had I left it that she
has this weird pattern

00:56:09.457 --> 00:56:11.919
that she keeps helping
when I tell her not to,

00:56:11.919 --> 00:56:14.466
that wouldn't been where it stayed.

00:56:14.466 --> 00:56:16.324
But when we talked about it,

00:56:16.324 --> 00:56:19.260
we really were able to figure it out.

00:56:19.260 --> 00:56:21.516
And it was a gift, I
think, to the both of us.

00:56:21.516 --> 00:56:24.380
Raised my awareness to
apply what I'd written about

00:56:24.380 --> 00:56:25.980
in my own life.

00:56:25.980 --> 00:56:28.799
People may not think I mean what I say.

00:56:28.799 --> 00:56:30.752
And for her to realize that sometimes

00:56:30.752 --> 00:56:33.502
people really mean what they say.

00:56:36.624 --> 00:56:38.575
So, meta-communicating.
- Thank you so much.

00:56:38.575 --> 00:56:39.575
- Thank you.

00:56:42.051 --> 00:56:43.384
Can you come up?

00:56:47.971 --> 00:56:50.048
- [Woman In White Shirt]
Thanks for your speech.

00:56:50.048 --> 00:56:52.310
I think the research you are doing is very

00:56:52.310 --> 00:56:54.172
interesting and exciting.

00:56:54.172 --> 00:56:57.039
And speaking of the friendship,

00:56:57.039 --> 00:57:01.934
I recall classical and
controversial old question,

00:57:01.934 --> 00:57:03.341
at least I think so.

00:57:03.341 --> 00:57:06.924
And do you think there
is a simple and pure

00:57:07.985 --> 00:57:11.796
friendship between a girl and a boy?

00:57:11.796 --> 00:57:14.706
- So the question is, is
simple, pure friendship

00:57:14.706 --> 00:57:16.741
possible between a girl and boy.

00:57:16.741 --> 00:57:18.451
Is that the question?
- Yeah.

00:57:18.451 --> 00:57:20.237
Friendship, just a friendship.

00:57:20.237 --> 00:57:23.996
Have nothing to do with
love relationship or other.

00:57:23.996 --> 00:57:25.906
Just a pure and simple
friendship between girl and boy.

00:57:25.906 --> 00:57:27.259
- Yeah, friendship.

00:57:27.259 --> 00:57:28.599
It's an interesting question.

00:57:28.599 --> 00:57:31.305
My short answer is, yes I do.

00:57:31.305 --> 00:57:35.123
But I'm thinking of
lesbians that I interviewed,

00:57:35.123 --> 00:57:36.299
who told me that they found,

00:57:36.299 --> 00:57:38.899
sometimes found it simpler,
one woman I'm thinking

00:57:38.899 --> 00:57:40.982
who I interviewed said, she found that her

00:57:40.982 --> 00:57:44.920
closest friends were
straight women and gay men.

00:57:44.920 --> 00:57:47.348
Because there was no confusion about

00:57:47.348 --> 00:57:50.553
what kind of friendship
it was going to be.

00:57:50.553 --> 00:57:53.981
And that in her group, if a woman somehow

00:57:53.981 --> 00:57:57.654
developed a crush on someone
that wasn't returned,

00:57:57.654 --> 00:57:59.936
it was sort of difficult for everybody.

00:57:59.936 --> 00:58:01.421
For the whole group.

00:58:01.421 --> 00:58:03.916
I'm thinking of women who told me that

00:58:03.916 --> 00:58:06.202
gay men are their closest friends.

00:58:06.202 --> 00:58:08.946
That's part of what
they told me about that.

00:58:08.946 --> 00:58:10.798
It was wonderful.

00:58:10.798 --> 00:58:12.101
They really loved the guy's company,

00:58:12.101 --> 00:58:14.484
but they don't have to
worry about that tension.

00:58:14.484 --> 00:58:17.366
So it think that layer is there.

00:58:17.366 --> 00:58:20.379
But yeah, I have encountered examples of

00:58:20.379 --> 00:58:22.723
if you want it, simple friendship.

00:58:22.723 --> 00:58:25.528
If simple means no sexual overtones.

00:58:25.528 --> 00:58:28.304
I do think it's possible.
- Thank you.

00:58:28.304 --> 00:58:32.304
- Good luck.
(audience laughing)

00:58:53.074 --> 00:58:54.196
- [Woman In Red Shirt] Hi,
I'm wondering if you have

00:58:54.196 --> 00:58:57.613
any suggestions about how to, as a woman,

00:58:59.212 --> 00:59:04.039
negotiate aspiration,
versus keeping your friends?

00:59:04.039 --> 00:59:06.422
- Aspiration versus--
- versus keeping your friends.

00:59:06.422 --> 00:59:09.550
You talked earlier about women,

00:59:09.550 --> 00:59:11.897
like the girls who kicked their friend out

00:59:11.897 --> 00:59:13.579
for being in the spelling bee.

00:59:13.579 --> 00:59:17.746
Any tips for diffusing that?
- Yeah, it's so complicated.

00:59:19.127 --> 00:59:23.112
I'm think again, real
anecdotes I heard about.

00:59:23.112 --> 00:59:26.820
Women telling me that
they felt their friends

00:59:26.820 --> 00:59:27.931
really stopped being their friends

00:59:27.931 --> 00:59:31.514
because they got a
higher job, or whatever.

00:59:33.063 --> 00:59:36.439
And sometimes it's just, if somebody has

00:59:36.439 --> 00:59:39.475
something you really want,
it's hard to be with them.

00:59:39.475 --> 00:59:41.047
So I'm thinking of a woman who told me,

00:59:41.047 --> 00:59:43.027
she had a baby, and a friend of hers

00:59:43.027 --> 00:59:44.580
who desperately wanted a baby,

00:59:44.580 --> 00:59:46.118
and wasn't able to get pregnant,

00:59:46.118 --> 00:59:49.186
just didn't wanna be with her
because it was so painful.

00:59:49.186 --> 00:59:53.019
And then later they
reunited, and got past it.

00:59:55.342 --> 00:59:56.759
So, what can you do about it?

00:59:56.759 --> 00:59:59.719
I guess my solution to everything is,

00:59:59.719 --> 01:00:03.602
you can try accommodating,
you can try talking about it.

01:00:03.602 --> 01:00:05.372
And then sometimes you just have to

01:00:05.372 --> 01:00:07.805
let it go for awhile, and see if you can

01:00:07.805 --> 01:00:09.638
come back to it later.

01:00:11.655 --> 01:00:13.009
Now you should know, I'm not a therapist,

01:00:13.009 --> 01:00:16.723
and I have no experience
on which I'm basing this.

01:00:16.723 --> 01:00:18.223
I'm just guessing.

01:00:19.303 --> 01:00:20.136
Thank you.

01:00:26.458 --> 01:00:27.457
- [Woman In Red And
White Shirt] Thank you.

01:00:27.457 --> 01:00:29.077
I've been a big fan of
your writing for awhile.

01:00:29.077 --> 01:00:31.264
- Thank you.
- So, in one of your books

01:00:31.264 --> 01:00:33.431
you talked about sympathy.

01:00:34.295 --> 01:00:37.413
And how men and women
perceive it very differently.

01:00:37.413 --> 01:00:39.600
- Sympathy.
- Yeah, and how women,

01:00:39.600 --> 01:00:42.872
when you, women friends,
when you express sympathy,

01:00:42.872 --> 01:00:44.536
they see it as the sameness,

01:00:44.536 --> 01:00:45.964
getting on the same level.

01:00:45.964 --> 01:00:48.701
And you could say the exact
same thing to a male friend,

01:00:48.701 --> 01:00:52.844
or a male partner, and they
view it as hierarchical.

01:00:52.844 --> 01:00:54.466
That you're putting them down.

01:00:54.466 --> 01:00:57.313
And I found that fascinating.

01:00:57.313 --> 01:00:59.139
And I've noticed that a lot.

01:00:59.139 --> 01:01:01.741
But I don't know how to navigate it.

01:01:01.741 --> 01:01:05.520
So if you could elaborate on that at all,

01:01:05.520 --> 01:01:06.569
that would be wonderful.

01:01:06.569 --> 01:01:08.003
Thank you.
- Yeah, I agree.

01:01:08.003 --> 01:01:09.257
It's fascinating.

01:01:09.257 --> 01:01:12.892
You know who helped me understand that?

01:01:12.892 --> 01:01:14.616
Robert Bly.

01:01:14.616 --> 01:01:16.037
Do you remember, around
the time that my book,

01:01:16.037 --> 01:01:18.845
You Just Don't Understand
was a Bestseller,

01:01:18.845 --> 01:01:21.174
Robert Bly has a book called Iron John,

01:01:21.174 --> 01:01:22.190
that was also best-selling.

01:01:22.190 --> 01:01:24.626
And we did a thing together.

01:01:24.626 --> 01:01:26.134
And he really helped me to understand.

01:01:26.134 --> 01:01:28.414
I never quite understood this myself.

01:01:28.414 --> 01:01:31.247
He said that sympathy seems to be,

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:34.083
like you said, a put down.

01:01:34.083 --> 01:01:37.166
And also a reminder of this bad thing

01:01:38.305 --> 01:01:40.048
that you wanna forget.

01:01:40.048 --> 01:01:42.787
So, he was saying for many men,

01:01:42.787 --> 01:01:44.381
the kindest thing you can do is

01:01:44.381 --> 01:01:46.257
act as if it didn't happen.

01:01:46.257 --> 01:01:47.685
(laughing)

01:01:47.685 --> 01:01:48.966
Help them forget it.

01:01:48.966 --> 01:01:51.049
Yeah, it's so widespread.

01:01:52.405 --> 01:01:55.569
And I have encountered
really serious issues

01:01:55.569 --> 01:01:58.305
among people who are close.

01:01:58.305 --> 01:02:01.509
One couple how had been
through 9/11 together.

01:02:01.509 --> 01:02:02.858
They had an apartment quite close

01:02:02.858 --> 01:02:04.856
to the World Trade Center.

01:02:04.856 --> 01:02:09.096
And so they had been
very traumatic for them.

01:02:09.096 --> 01:02:10.856
And the wife wanted to talk about it,

01:02:10.856 --> 01:02:12.733
and the husband didn't.

01:02:12.733 --> 01:02:15.268
And the more she wanted to
talk about it and he wouldn't,

01:02:15.268 --> 01:02:17.662
the more alienated she felt,
the more alone she felt,

01:02:17.662 --> 01:02:19.813
the more let down she felt.

01:02:19.813 --> 01:02:21.360
And the more she kept
trying to talk about,

01:02:21.360 --> 01:02:24.194
when what he really wanted
to do was not talk about it,

01:02:24.194 --> 01:02:27.027
and move on, was upsetting to him.

01:02:28.109 --> 01:02:31.294
So I guess I'm gonna sound
like a broken record,

01:02:31.294 --> 01:02:34.227
but it think if they had talked about it,

01:02:34.227 --> 01:02:37.244
and kind of come to an
understanding of why

01:02:37.244 --> 01:02:39.557
each of them is reacting
this different way,

01:02:39.557 --> 01:02:42.143
then maybe they could
figure out a compromise.

01:02:42.143 --> 01:02:45.198
And that's what, you
know, what I'm called by

01:02:45.198 --> 01:02:47.674
journalists about all
these things I write about,

01:02:47.674 --> 01:02:50.683
they always wanna know tips.

01:02:50.683 --> 01:02:51.708
What can you do?

01:02:51.708 --> 01:02:52.827
What's the tip?

01:02:52.827 --> 01:02:54.495
And I always say, I
can't give tips because

01:02:54.495 --> 01:02:57.040
each situation is different.

01:02:57.040 --> 01:02:59.178
Each person is different.

01:02:59.178 --> 01:03:01.800
The tip I give is understanding.

01:03:01.800 --> 01:03:04.403
If you both understand what's going on,

01:03:04.403 --> 01:03:07.038
then you can decide how to proceed.

01:03:07.038 --> 01:03:10.442
And so you might decide,
I might just have to

01:03:10.442 --> 01:03:12.138
not offer sympathy.

01:03:12.138 --> 01:03:13.584
It makes me feel bad, because I think

01:03:13.584 --> 01:03:16.197
I'm letting him down, or I
should be offering sympathy.

01:03:16.197 --> 01:03:17.920
But I realize that's what he wants.

01:03:17.920 --> 01:03:21.577
So I'm giving him the
gift of what he wants.

01:03:21.577 --> 01:03:25.570
And he might have to learn
to offer some sympathy.

01:03:25.570 --> 01:03:29.494
Because that's what
might be helpful to you.

01:03:29.494 --> 01:03:30.639
So I don't know if that's hugely helpful,

01:03:30.639 --> 01:03:32.556
but that's my thoughts.

01:03:35.121 --> 01:03:36.160
Hi.

01:03:36.160 --> 01:03:37.657
- [Woman In Red Shirt]
First I wanna say thank you

01:03:37.657 --> 01:03:39.574
very much for your
research and your writing.

01:03:39.574 --> 01:03:41.491
I used your research on

01:03:43.856 --> 01:03:46.553
gender differences in
communication when I was

01:03:46.553 --> 01:03:47.951
teaching at the college level,

01:03:47.951 --> 01:03:49.929
and now the teacher has
become student again.

01:03:49.929 --> 01:03:52.747
And so my questions is pertaining to,

01:03:52.747 --> 01:03:54.101
if you're doing any research,

01:03:54.101 --> 01:03:56.183
or the research of your colleagues on

01:03:56.183 --> 01:03:59.089
intergenerational differences
in terms of friendship.

01:03:59.089 --> 01:04:00.756
I'm in my early 50s.

01:04:01.594 --> 01:04:05.940
I have, I'm probably,
I'm near the top end.

01:04:05.940 --> 01:04:09.284
I'm at one of the seminaries
here through the GTU.

01:04:09.284 --> 01:04:13.098
And a lot of my colleagues
are in their 20s and 30s.

01:04:13.098 --> 01:04:15.476
They're the age of my adult children.

01:04:15.476 --> 01:04:18.584
They're the age, a little bit older than

01:04:18.584 --> 01:04:20.707
the age of the students I used to teach.

01:04:20.707 --> 01:04:22.957
And just a general trend is

01:04:24.081 --> 01:04:25.248
circumspect...

01:04:30.277 --> 01:04:31.110
Reticent.

01:04:32.583 --> 01:04:34.301
And I can do the whole texting,

01:04:34.301 --> 01:04:35.698
and the social media thing.

01:04:35.698 --> 01:04:37.639
But I have a sibling that's
only two and a half years

01:04:37.639 --> 01:04:39.579
younger than myself, and her primary mode

01:04:39.579 --> 01:04:41.197
of communication is through texting.

01:04:41.197 --> 01:04:43.684
Some of this may be addressed
in your talk tomorrow,

01:04:43.684 --> 01:04:47.851
but is conversation, is
intimacy through conversation

01:04:49.329 --> 01:04:51.979
becoming a lost art,
as those of us that are

01:04:51.979 --> 01:04:56.042
in the boomer generation, and
maybe some of the Gen-Xers

01:04:56.042 --> 01:04:58.459
continue to age and fade out?

01:04:59.367 --> 01:05:00.370
- Yeah.

01:05:00.370 --> 01:05:02.792
I will have a bit to say,
a lot to say tomorrow

01:05:02.792 --> 01:05:06.039
about generational differences
and use of social media.

01:05:06.039 --> 01:05:09.372
But especially the mechanics of it.

01:05:09.372 --> 01:05:12.273
And assumptions about what's
appropriate and what's not.

01:05:12.273 --> 01:05:16.786
And use of punctuation, and
other markers like that.

01:05:16.786 --> 01:05:18.833
But the question of
friendships across age,

01:05:18.833 --> 01:05:20.580
I have a bit to say about it in the book,

01:05:20.580 --> 01:05:22.794
but not a whole lot.

01:05:22.794 --> 01:05:26.424
And sometimes what people
told me in those interviews

01:05:26.424 --> 01:05:28.752
about friendships with older or younger,

01:05:28.752 --> 01:05:30.323
much older or much younger friends,

01:05:30.323 --> 01:05:33.764
often ended up being about social media.

01:05:33.764 --> 01:05:36.764
Like students saying that she really

01:05:37.605 --> 01:05:39.759
considered this older
friend a good friend,

01:05:39.759 --> 01:05:41.379
but that friend didn't understand that

01:05:41.379 --> 01:05:44.501
having a Facebook page open didn't mean

01:05:44.501 --> 01:05:47.993
she was actually open for interaction.

01:05:47.993 --> 01:05:51.765
She might be in class with
the Facebook page open.

01:05:51.765 --> 01:05:53.098
Not in my class.

01:05:54.020 --> 01:05:56.269
I don't allow it.

01:05:56.269 --> 01:05:59.407
But yeah, no I'm sure there's
more to say about that

01:05:59.407 --> 01:06:02.125
in maybe a future book.

01:06:02.125 --> 01:06:02.958
Thank you.

01:06:12.845 --> 01:06:13.857
- [Woman In White Shirt]
Since it's welcome back

01:06:13.857 --> 01:06:17.502
to Berkeley, I wanna ask
a political question.

01:06:17.502 --> 01:06:20.802
So we're reading, we're
hearing from many people

01:06:20.802 --> 01:06:23.434
we have to learn to talk with people

01:06:23.434 --> 01:06:27.023
and listen to people
with whom we don't agree.

01:06:27.023 --> 01:06:30.818
And I think it's one more layer about

01:06:30.818 --> 01:06:34.416
what are your values,
in addition to all these

01:06:34.416 --> 01:06:37.743
things you say about rituals and styles.

01:06:37.743 --> 01:06:39.660
So it feels impossible.

01:06:41.376 --> 01:06:44.459
I don't think I want tips, but maybe,

01:06:46.083 --> 01:06:47.657
maybe I do want tips.

01:06:47.657 --> 01:06:51.152
But do you have any
insight that could help us?

01:06:51.152 --> 01:06:54.388
- I'm asked about that a lot.

01:06:54.388 --> 01:06:58.643
I wrote a book called
The Argument Culture.

01:06:58.643 --> 01:07:00.626
It was published in 1998,

01:07:00.626 --> 01:07:02.802
but I think it's more
true, and more accurate

01:07:02.802 --> 01:07:06.006
and relevant today than
it was even back then.

01:07:06.006 --> 01:07:08.009
And the point I made there is that our

01:07:08.009 --> 01:07:10.443
public discourse is polarizing,

01:07:10.443 --> 01:07:13.479
because we turn everything into a fight.

01:07:13.479 --> 01:07:15.062
And the news media,

01:07:17.945 --> 01:07:21.535
and politics certainly,
they exaggerate that.

01:07:21.535 --> 01:07:23.814
They don't find people to put on who are

01:07:23.814 --> 01:07:25.242
somewhere in the middle.

01:07:25.242 --> 01:07:28.959
They find the most extreme
sides that they can find,

01:07:28.959 --> 01:07:31.244
even if they have to scour the fringes

01:07:31.244 --> 01:07:33.677
of lunacy to find them.

01:07:33.677 --> 01:07:36.041
And they won't even cover
something if there isn't

01:07:36.041 --> 01:07:38.835
another side, and they make
everything into two sides,

01:07:38.835 --> 01:07:40.503
where most things are not two sides.

01:07:40.503 --> 01:07:42.199
There are many sides.

01:07:42.199 --> 01:07:43.859
And I think what we're reaping now,

01:07:43.859 --> 01:07:46.776
is the harvest of that being a norm

01:07:48.068 --> 01:07:50.557
in our public discourse over so long.

01:07:50.557 --> 01:07:53.844
And it has crept into
personal relationships.

01:07:53.844 --> 01:07:55.441
I think people are more confrontational,

01:07:55.441 --> 01:07:58.736
more belligerent in
private attraction now,

01:07:58.736 --> 01:08:01.986
because of that tone being so pervasive

01:08:03.503 --> 01:08:05.003
in our public discourse.

01:08:05.003 --> 01:08:06.771
And I think it's corrosive.

01:08:06.771 --> 01:08:09.684
Corrosive to the human spirit.

01:08:09.684 --> 01:08:11.374
The specific question.

01:08:11.374 --> 01:08:13.238
Everyone's telling us now
you have to talk to people

01:08:13.238 --> 01:08:16.482
that you don't agree with,
and how do we do that?

01:08:16.482 --> 01:08:18.184
I've certainly encountered the phenomemon

01:08:18.184 --> 01:08:21.181
that people are less likely to do it now.

01:08:21.181 --> 01:08:24.793
People who won't go home
to their relatives because,

01:08:24.793 --> 01:08:27.102
okay, they knew that their
relatives were Republican.

01:08:27.102 --> 01:08:30.000
That was okay, they put it aside.

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:32.832
But now, knowing somebody voted for Trump

01:08:32.832 --> 01:08:36.582
they feel is so, that
ramifications have been

01:08:37.745 --> 01:08:41.007
so terrible that they just
don't wanna deal with it.

01:08:41.007 --> 01:08:43.090
Okay, I'll say one thing.

01:08:44.814 --> 01:08:47.670
I have read that if you talk to people you

01:08:47.670 --> 01:08:50.254
don't agree with, our
impulse it to tell them

01:08:50.254 --> 01:08:52.461
what we think, and change their minds.

01:08:52.461 --> 01:08:53.898
And nobody changes their mind because

01:08:53.898 --> 01:08:55.914
of something you told them.

01:08:55.914 --> 01:08:58.081
But if you listen to them,

01:08:58.081 --> 01:09:02.906
and have them tell you
everything that they think,

01:09:02.906 --> 01:09:05.251
and you really listen, and
you really consider it,

01:09:05.251 --> 01:09:08.554
that if you then eventually
work your way around

01:09:08.554 --> 01:09:09.974
to showing another perspective,

01:09:09.974 --> 01:09:11.750
they'd be more likely to hear it.

01:09:11.750 --> 01:09:15.250
So, maybe that's one little bit of advice.

01:09:16.094 --> 01:09:17.604
I think we're done.

01:09:17.604 --> 01:09:18.497
(audience applauding)

01:09:18.497 --> 01:09:19.330
Thank you.

01:09:25.607 --> 01:09:28.190
(upbeat music)

